Architecture plan for Issue #1: Initialize Vite + TypeScript project

Scope source:
- GitHub Issue #1 requests a Vite vanilla TypeScript project with package.json,
  tsconfig.json, vite.config.ts, index.html, a full-window canvas element, and
  reset CSS.
- No PRODUCT.md is present in the workspace, so no product brand beyond the
  repository/issue wording is assumed.

Module structure and file organization:
- package.json: define Node/Vite scripts for dev, build, and preview.
- vite.config.ts: keep the initial Vite config minimal unless deployment needs a
  base path later.
- tsconfig.json: strict TypeScript settings suitable for browser code.
- index.html: single app entry point with a root/full-window canvas element.
- src/main.ts: bootstrap browser behavior and own canvas sizing/setup.
- src/style.css: reset CSS plus full-viewport layout rules.
- Future shared types should live under src/types.ts or src/types/ once more
  than one module consumes them.

Dependencies between issues:
- Issue #1 is the foundation for all later work. Later sessions should build on
  the Vite app shell instead of replacing it.
- Canvas rendering, input handling, and domain modules should depend on the
  bootstrap created here, not on global inline scripts.

Key design decisions:
- Use the vanilla-ts Vite template shape to keep the baseline small and explicit.
- Treat the canvas as the primary application surface from the first commit.
- Keep styling limited to reset and viewport layout until product requirements
  define actual visual design.
- Avoid adding frameworks or rendering libraries during setup unless a later
  issue explicitly requires one.
